[
    {
        "content": "<p>Hi everyone, I have the following question: Is the Q-construction over an exact category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{E}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span></span></span></span>  yielding a triangulated category? Or not always?  I just wanna make sure I got it right. Thanks!</p>",
        "id": 519632164,
        "sender_full_name": "Federica Pasqualone",
        "timestamp": 1747838790
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>No, I think you have a level shift there. Algebraic K-theory of an exact (or Waldhausen or stable <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo>−</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\infty-</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mord\">−</span></span></span></span>) category is a single spectrum, not a whole triangulated category.</p>",
        "id": 519666149,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Carlson",
        "timestamp": 1747848386
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"609515\">@Kevin Carlson</span> ! Actually I was  wondering about <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Σ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Sigma</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Σ</span></span></span></span>, i.e. the shift. Because one takes equivalence classes of spans of admissible monic epic ...</p>",
        "id": 519669989,
        "sender_full_name": "Federica Pasqualone",
        "timestamp": 1747849878
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Well the K-theory comes later, it is the loop space of the geometric realization of the nerve of the Quillen construction, i.e. <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>K</mi><mrow><mo fence=\"true\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi><mo fence=\"true\">)</mo></mrow><mo>:</mo><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi><mi>N</mi><mi>Q</mi><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K\\left(\\mathcal{E}\\right) := \\Omega|NQ\\mathcal{E}|</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"minner\"><span class=\"mopen delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span><span class=\"mclose delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\">)</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Ω∣</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">NQ</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span><span class=\"mord\">∣</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 519670524,
        "sender_full_name": "Federica Pasqualone",
        "timestamp": 1747850044
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ah, I see what you were thinking; I tend to think of the Q-construction as going all the way to the algebraic K-theory. I don't remember basically any details about the category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Q</mi><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Q\\mathcal E</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Q</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span></span></span></span> but I'd be a bit shocked if it were triangulated. Do you know <em>any</em> of the appropriate properties?</p>",
        "id": 519671248,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Carlson",
        "timestamp": 1747850311
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I am meditating on the shift  <span aria-label=\"woman in lotus position\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f9d8-200d-2640\" role=\"img\" title=\"woman in lotus position\">:woman_in_lotus_position:</span> <span aria-label=\"rolling on the floor laughing\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f923\" role=\"img\" title=\"rolling on the floor laughing\">:rolling_on_the_floor_laughing:</span></p>",
        "id": 519671949,
        "sender_full_name": "Federica Pasqualone",
        "timestamp": 1747850552
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It should be that one  takes an exact category and defines the morphisms as equivalence classes of spans of admissible mono-epis (the objects are the same as the original exact category). Here you are <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Q</mi><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Q\\mathcal{E}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Q</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 519672156,
        "sender_full_name": "Federica Pasqualone",
        "timestamp": 1747850631
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For the triangulated category, if this is what you were referring to, we need to define in fact a triangulation (<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Σ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Sigma</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Σ</span></span></span></span> and a class of distinguished triangles) satisfying certain  axioms.</p>",
        "id": 519673225,
        "sender_full_name": "Federica Pasqualone",
        "timestamp": 1747850984
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Add to the list of Federica's thoughts that the derived category of an Abelian one is indeed triangulated...</p>",
        "id": 519673868,
        "sender_full_name": "Federica Pasqualone",
        "timestamp": 1747851194
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"705200\">Federica Pasqualone</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Of.20Q-constructions.20and.20other.20demons/near/519673868\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Add to the list of Federica's thoughts that the derived category of an Abelian one is indeed triangulated...</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>You actually don't need Abelian here, you can define derived categories also for exact categories, and these are triangulated as well! This is covered in \"Exact categories\" by Bühler.</p>",
        "id": 519676714,
        "sender_full_name": "Antonio Lorenzin",
        "timestamp": 1747852183
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Then we are back to the question about <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Q</mi><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Q\\mathcal{E}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Q</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span></span></span></span> ...  (it's a loop space <span aria-label=\"rolling on the floor laughing\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f923\" role=\"img\" title=\"rolling on the floor laughing\">:rolling_on_the_floor_laughing:</span> ) Thanks <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"419640\">@Antonio Lorenzin</span> !</p>",
        "id": 519677112,
        "sender_full_name": "Federica Pasqualone",
        "timestamp": 1747852315
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>And since you mentioned them <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"609515\">@Kevin Carlson</span> , <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>S</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">∙</mo></msub><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S_{\\bullet} \\mathcal{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1611em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0576em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">∙</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span></span></span></span> of a Waldhausen is Waldhausen, but we have to switch to Reedy cofibrations. If we take levelwise cofibrations, what goes wrong? Well ...</p>",
        "id": 519916616,
        "sender_full_name": "Federica Pasqualone",
        "timestamp": 1747946031
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">∙</mo></msub><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mo>⊆</mo><mtext mathvariant=\"bold\">Fun</mtext><mrow><mo fence=\"true\">(</mo><mtext mathvariant=\"bold\">Ar</mtext><mrow><mo fence=\"true\">[</mo><mo>∙</mo><mo fence=\"true\">]</mo></mrow><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mo fence=\"true\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{S}_{\\bullet}\\mathcal{C} \\subseteq \\textbf{Fun}\\left(\\textbf{Ar}\\left[\\bullet\\right], \\mathcal{C}\\right)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1611em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.075em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">∙</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊆</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textbf\">Fun</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"minner\"><span class=\"mopen delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\">(</span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord textbf\">Ar</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"minner\"><span class=\"mopen delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\">[</span><span class=\"mord\">∙</span><span class=\"mclose delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\">]</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\">)</span></span></span></span></span> is a full subcategory inclusion with objects such that the tail of the lattice progressively reduces to a unique zero. Now the latching object, ...</p>",
